        <div type="letter">
            <div type="text">
                <opener>
                    <placeName><hi rend="smallCaps">Down, | Beckenham, Kent, | Railway Station, | Orpington, S.E.R.</hi></placeName>
                    <date>April 7th, 1880.</date>
                    <seg type="supplemental"><hi rend="italic">Via</hi> <hi rend="smallCaps">Brindisi.</hi></seg>
                    <salute><hi rend="smallCaps">Dear Sir,</hi></salute>
                </opener>
                <div type="transcription">
                     
<p>The subject to which you refer in your letter of February 15th seems to me a curious one, which may turn out interesting; but I am sorry to say that I am most unfortunately situated for offering you any assistance. I live in the country, and from weak health seldom see anyone. I will, however, forward your letter to Mr. F. Galton, who is the most likely man that I can think of to take up the subject to make further enquiries.<ref target="#foot.f1"/></p>
                    <p>Wishing you success, | I remain, dear Sir, | Yours faithfully, | <hi rend="smallCaps">Charles Darwin.</hi></p> 
                </div>
            </div>

            
        </div>
        
        
        <div type="footnotes">
            <note xml:id="foot.f1">See <ref target="./DCP-LETT-12488.xml">letter from Henry Faulds, 16 February 1880</ref> and n. 1. Faulds had discussed the merits of keeping a record of fingerprints, focusing particularly on their possible use in identifying criminals. See <ref target="./DCP-LETT-12565.xml">letter to Francis Galton, 7 April 1880</ref>.</note>
        </div>
    
